Q10.11: I strongly believe that a recommended coronavirus vaccine, when it becomes available, will have been thoroughly tested through extensive trials to establish its safety as well as its efficacy against the pandemic coronavirus. Therefore the vaccine will be beneficial and effective, and getting vaccinated will be the wise choice.
Q12.2: I can't be sure about the purpose of the game, but apparently it tested participants' optimization behavior in a choice scenario (where, at each step of the game, participants were asked to chose any one of the three illustrated characters, to obtain a resulting score increment [+100] or decrement [-50], while each illustrated character's scoring performance could vary during the test). The goal for participants was to select a choice that the participant presumed likely to obtain a positive score at each step, aiming to maximize the game's total score.  I assume the researchers will use the results to study patterns of choice behavior (and probably correlate this with responses from other parts of the survey), although I can't be sure what conclusions the researchers may draw from this.
Q12.3: Upon receiving a negative score, I usually tended to "switch" or "rotate" experimentally to the other choices in turn, to see if I could immediately get a positive score from one of them.  Then, after a choice produced a positive score, I'd tentatively select that choice again repeatedly to see if it would continue to return a series of positive scores.  Eventually it would return another negative score, and then (after one or two negatives) I'd probably again rotate through the choices until obtaining another positive score. ... Although I considered other strategies (such as "loyalty" or hesitating to switch, or tracking histories to inform my decisions), I realized that I wasn't sure if any such alternative strategy would be optimal or not.
Q12.4: Although I did vary my choice behavior slightly (such as with brief periods of "loyalty" to a choice that had generated a long sequence of positive scores, or alternatively sometimes switching choices "randomly" without reason), I realized that I wasn't sure what strategy would be optimal, so I usually reverted to my simplistic strategy (repeating a choice after a positive score, and switching after one or two negatives).
Q12.6: The question about 'deliberate sabotage' seems to allude to conscious behavior.  It was apparent that the illustrated player characters must be software-simulated, so I cannot attribute any conscious behavior or motives to them.  Although it's possible that such a software program might vary its response patterns in ways a participant cannot anticipate (e.g. by varying its response logic reactively or randomly), I wouldn't call this "deliberate sabotage" but rather just a pre-programmed aspect of the experiment. ... In any case, I didn't notice any significant behavioral differences between the scoring performance of the three illustrated characters (except perhaps the middle one might have tended to produce negative results more frequently than the others, but I wasn't sure if that was true or if I was merely imagining it, so I tried not to let it bias my simple rotation strategy.)
